arctgz(7)						Miscellaneous Information Manual					      arctgz(7)

NAME
       arctgz - safety-first project initialisation and configuration management library for the arctgz archive format

SYNOPSIS
       use arctgz::{init, load_config, save_config, ArctgzConfig, ArctgzError};
       use std::path::Path;

       fn init(project_path: &Path, force: bool) -> Result<(), ArctgzError>;
       fn load_config(project_path: &Path) -> Result<ArctgzConfig, ArctgzError>;
       fn save_config(project_path: &Path, config: &ArctgzConfig) -> Result<(), ArctgzError>;

       struct ArctgzConfig {
	   pub name:	String,
	   pub version: String,
	   pub include: Vec<String>,
       }

       impl ArctgzConfig {
	   pub fn validate(&self) -> Result<(), ArctgzError>;
       }

       enum ArctgzError { ... }

DESCRIPTION
       The  arctgz library provides a safe, cross-platform API for initialising and managing arctgz project directories.  It enforces path con‐
       finement, validates metadata before touching the filesystem, and performs atomic file operations to prevent corruption and TOCTOU races.

       The core functionality includes:

       • init() – scaffold a new project directory with a default configuration and an empty resource folder.

       • load_config() – read and validate an existing project configuration.

       • save_config() – atomically write a validated configuration back to disk.

       All paths are resolved with std::fs::canonicalize() (equivalent to realpath(3)), so symbolic links are followed during  the  home-direc‐
       tory confinement check.	The library is fully tested on Linux, macOS, and Windows.

FUNCTIONS
       init(project_path, force)
	      Initialises a new arctgz project at project_path.

	      Arguments:

		     project_path
			    A  reference  to  a std::path::Path.  The path must not be empty and must reside (after canonicalisation) under the
			    current user's home directory.  If the path does not exist, it will be created; otherwise it must be a directory.

		     force  If true, skip the non-empty directory check.  However, an existing arctgz.init file will still cause an AlreadyIni‐
			    tialized error.

	      Return value:
		     Ok(()) on success, or an ArctgzError describing the failure.

	      Side effects (only after all safety checks pass):

		     • Creates the project directory (and parents, if needed).

		     • Creates the include/ subdirectory.

		     • Writes a default arctgz.init configuration file atomically (using create_new(true)).

	      Security checks (performed before any filesystem modification):

		     • Home directory confinement – the canonicalised project path must start with the canonicalised home  directory.	Symlink
		       attacks are neutralised.

		     • Path validity – rejects empty paths, and rejects existing files (as opposed to directories).

		     • Directory emptiness (unless force is true).

       load_config(project_path)
	      Reads and validates the arctgz.init file from the given project directory.

	      Arguments:

		     project_path
			    Path to the project root (must contain an arctgz.init file).

	      Return value:
		     Ok(ArctgzConfig) if the file exists, contains valid JSON, and passes validate().  On failure, returns an ArctgzError vari‐
		     ant (ConfigNotFound, ConfigLoadError, or ConfigValidation).

       save_config(project_path, config)
	      Writes a validated ArctgzConfig back to the project's arctgz.init file atomically.  The operation first writes the JSON to a tem‐
	      porary file (arctgz.tmp) and then renames it over the original.  This prevents corruption if the process crashes mid-write.

	      Arguments:

		     project_path
			    Path to the project root.

		     config An ArctgzConfig instance to save.  Must pass validate() before saving.

	      Return value:
		     Ok(()) on success, or an ArctgzError (ConfigValidation, ConfigSaveError, or Json).

TYPES
       ArctgzConfig
	      Represents the project configuration stored in arctgz.init.

       Fields:

	      name   Project name (default "untitled").	 Valid characters: alphanumeric, -, and _.  Maximum length 255 characters.

	      version
		     Semantic version string (default "0.1.0"), validated against the semver crate.

	      include
		     List  of  relative resource paths (default []).  Each path must be relative, must not contain .. (parent directory) compo‐
		     nents, and the list may contain at most 100 entries.

       validate()
       Validates all fields according to the rules above.  Returns Ok(()) or an ArctgzError::ConfigValidation with a human-readable message.

       The struct is serialised/deserialised with #[serde(deny_unknown_fields)], so unknown JSON keys in the configuration file	 will  cause  a
       deserialisation error.

       ArctgzError
	      An enumeration covering all failure cases.  Each variant holds a descriptive message (or source error) to aid debugging.

       Variants:

	      Io(std::io::Error)
		     Filesystem I/O error (e.g., creating directories, writing files).

	      Json(serde_json::Error)
		     JSON serialisation or deserialisation failure.

	      AlreadyInitialized
		     An arctgz.init file already exists in the target directory during init().

	      InvalidPath(String)
		     The supplied path is empty or is an existing file, not a directory.

	      PathNotAllowed(String)
		     The canonicalised project path lies outside the user's home directory.

	      DirectoryNotEmpty(String)
		     The target directory exists, is not empty, and force was false.

	      ConfigValidation(String)
		     A configuration validation rule failed (e.g., invalid name, version, or include).

	      ConfigNotFound(String)
		     load_config() could not find the arctgz.init file.

	      ConfigLoadError(String)
		     load_config() encountered an I/O error or invalid JSON.

	      ConfigSaveError(String)
		     save_config() failed during the write or rename step.

EXAMPLE
   Basic initialisation
       use std::path::Path;
       use arctgz;

       fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
	   let project_path = Path::new("./my-project");
	   arctgz::init(project_path, false)?;
	   println!("Project created.");
	   Ok(())
       }

       After running the above, the directory looks like:
       my-project/
       -- arctgz.init
       -- include/

   Editing configuration
       use arctgz::{load_config, save_config};

       fn configure(project: &std::path::Path) -> Result<(), arctgz::ArctgzError> {
	   let mut config = load_config(project)?;
	   config.name = "hello-world".into();
	   config.include.push("assets".into());
	   save_config(project, &config)?;
	   Ok(())
       }

FILES
       arctgz.init
	      JSON  configuration  file.   Written atomically by init() and save_config().  The library never truncates an existing file unless
	      explicitly overwritten via save_config().

       include/
	      An empty directory created during initialisation.	 It is intended to hold resource files for later compilation/archiving.

ENVIRONMENT
       HOME (Unix) / USERPROFILE (Windows)
	      The library obtains the current user's home directory through the dirs crate.  If the variable is not  set,  a  platform-specific
	      fallback	is attempted.  If no home directory can be determined, init() will fail with PathNotAllowed for any path (even relative
	      ones) because confinement cannot be verified.

SECURITY
       • Path confinement: only paths inside the canonicalised home directory are allowed.  Symlink traversal is fully mitigated by  canonical‐
	 ising both the project path and the home directory.

       • No  side  effects before validation: init() resolves the path and performs all security checks before creating any directories.  Thus,
	 even a failed call with a path outside the home directory will not leave unwanted directories on disk.

       • Atomic configuration writes: the use of create_new(true) for  init()  prevents	 TOCTOU	 attacks  when	creating  the  initial	config.
	 save_config() writes to a temporary file and renames, ensuring the configuration file is never left in an incomplete state.

       • Input	validation:  configuration  fields  are strictly validated.  Unknown JSON keys are rejected, preventing accidental or malicious
	 settings from entering the project metadata.

NOTES
       The library is intended to be used as a building block for higher-level tools.  It does not impose  any	locking	 mechanism;  concurrent
       calls  on the same directory may race (see TOCTOU considerations in the security section).  Users should serialise access when operating
       on the same project from multiple processes or threads.

VERSION
       arctgz 0.3.0 – project initialisation and configuration management are implemented.  Future releases will introduce archive compilation,
       verification, and extraction.

SEE ALSO
       semver(7), realpath(3), serde_json(5), dirs(7)

BUGS
       • The include/ directory is always created empty; there is no add command yet.  Use load_config/save_config to manage the  include  list
	 manually.

       • Concurrent  init  calls  on the same path are not serialised and may lead to one process failing with AlreadyInitialized while another
	 has already created the directory.

       • The library does not clean up the include/ directory if the configuration write fails halfway through initialisation.

